@chibiapegang @derktargin1 What else has visa collected. Yes Visa was def not biz dev. But it sent floor from 40 ‚Äî> 125. Insane impact.
@chibiapegang @derktargin1 I think it was a classic web2 partnership. Both sides promoted the other to their distribution. Yuga is extremely good at biz dev.  Marketing geniuses.
@derktargin1 @chibiapegang Yeah it was a good deal for both parties. I think the visa punk had a similar impact but it was less of a BD deal and more of a symbolic purchase.

@chibiapegang Larva is definitely against plagiarism or other people profiting by selling copies of their art. If that‚Äôs anti web3 I‚Äôd agree. BAYC is no different. The v1 debacle was extremely tough but I agree Larva fumbled from a PR perspective. But that was after the IP thing.
@chibiapegang How many v1 do you have?  I have one punk and one v1.

@chibiapegang Also. I own 1 ape, 1 mutant and 3 kennels. Have about 2x the BAYC exposure vs punk exposure. I just think the world was uniquely anti Larva as opposed to standing for any big principals.

@chibiapegang Also keep in mind, the Adidas deal was a joint biz dev relationship. Adidas got the BAYC distribution and promotion of their NFT & in exchange advertised for BAYC. This was not just a thing where Adidas loved BAYC and therefore paid 100 ETH for an ape and built a brand around it.

@DrJones0305 Yep. Everyone is trying to enter the gaming world and other spaces to prove ‚Äúutility‚Äù but the fact is that the biggest whales in gaming spend 10 ETH in a year. That‚Äôs the price of a decent Kennel.
@NouNft Yes. I‚Äôm not anti derivs. Especially if an artist signs onto CC0. I just don‚Äôt believe they add value to the original set.
@chibiapegang BAYC when they DMCA‚Äôd Phunky apes?
@chibiapegang A lot of cool projects are using punks. The reason they aren‚Äôt lately is because punks are out of fashion. Not cause of the IP stuff that has never been enforced on anyone ever.
@chibiapegang There was the same retaliation against phunky apes. They got DMCA‚Äôed and no one cared at all. No different from phunks. Off Opensea forever.

@chibiapegang Just not true. Any company is capable of getting in touch with Larva just like Adidas did with Yuga. It was a pre-done deal. And companies *have* bought punks before. 

Either way - NFT twitter‚Äôs rage about it was absurd.
@chibiapegang People use punks for all sorts of things too and no one cares at all. Non issue.

@chibiapegang Yes. Agree that punks have a unique place in this world. Also think punks will give IP to holders soon. And as my original post said, that will change *absolutely nothing* because no one really cares about this at all, once they‚Äôre done throwing eggs at Larva.
@chibiapegang I just don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs a real issue. All theoretical. Any brand could do the same with Doodles and Doodles will love it.
@chibiapegang The Adidas deal was worked out with Yuga. They could have easily done a deal with Larva. Larva would have loved it. Zero IP issues.

@chibiapegang I think Adidas could have and Larva would have loved it. Larva just isn‚Äôt into marketing anymore. Visa bought a punk and very easily could have made it pfp and monetized and it would have been great for all parties. Larva just isn‚Äôt in that game anymore.

I see both sides.

@chibiapegang I‚Äôm just saying (a) no one is making $100k/year off their NFT and (b) Larva has shown zero interest in enforcing anything ever. I think the whole fiasco was just people being anti Larva.

@chibiapegang It is just a view not saying MFers are proof. I think there‚Äôs a reasonable case that derivs increase exposure and help but I increasingly think that‚Äôs not really helping. Certainly don‚Äôt have scientific proof just my sense.

@chibiapegang No punk owner has ever had any problem with anything related to IP. Ever. Larva has never gone after a punk owner for everything. For all intents & purposes punk owners can do whatever they want.
